<subSubSection id="8CD2ECDBE47AFF96FF0FFE800DEFB1C3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C477BF50E47AFF96FF0FFE800DEFB1C3" blockId="19.[151,1436,356,703]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FF0FFE800C21B201" bold="true" box="[151,280,356,381]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Comments</emphasis>
. After studying specimens at the 
<collectionCode id="A2D92795E47AFF96FD20FE800FCBB200" box="[696,754,356,380]" country="Canada" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/y2kv-9w3k" name="Canadian National Collection of Insects, Arachnids, and Nematodes" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">CNC</collectionCode>
identified as 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FC06FE810900B200" authority="Curran" authorityName="Curran" box="[926,1081,356,380]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Baccha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grata">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FC06FE810EE2B200" box="[926,987,357,380]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">grata</emphasis>
Curran
</taxonomicName>
, the male genitalia and wing characters are similar to the ones of 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FDDFFE630FA3B2DC" box="[583,666,391,416]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Baccha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="placiva">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FDDFFE630FA3B2DC" box="[583,666,391,416]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">placiva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FD40FE6D0E68B2DC" box="[728,849,393,416]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ocyptamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conjunctus">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FD40FE6D0E68B2DC" box="[728,849,393,416]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">conjunctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see comments below in 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FB1AFE6309ECB2DC" box="[1154,1237,391,416]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Baccha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="placiva">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FB1AFE6309ECB2DC" box="[1154,1237,391,416]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">placiva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The abdominal markings are similar to those two species, but 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FD63FE490E01B2B8" box="[763,824,429,452]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Baccha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grata">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FD63FE490E01B2B8" box="[763,824,429,452]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">grata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an only slightly petiolate abdomen and its basoflagellomere is remarkably bifurcated in both sexes (a character seen so far in species of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FF0FFE100C05B171" box="[151,316,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Microdontinae">Microdontinae</taxonomicName>
and in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FD9CFE110F8BB171" authority="Hull" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1936" box="[516,690,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cacoceria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F6BC6342E47AFF96FD9CFE110F40B170" box="[516,633,501,524]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Cacoceria</emphasis>
Hull
</taxonomicName>
of the 
<taxonomicName id="03C8C4D3E47AFF96FC9BFE100EB9B171" authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1834" box="[771,896,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Eristalinae">Eristalinae</taxonomicName>
). Other unique characters of this species are the male abdominal segment 5 and genitalia flexed dorsally, positioned perpendicular to the rest of the abdomen, tergum 4 with deep concave apical margin and sternum 4 with pair of acute projections apically. The female terga 5 and 6 are slightly asymmetric. It is unfortunate that when 
<bibRefCitation id="A059C2A1E47AFF96FCB3FD840EF2B104" box="[811,971,608,632]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refId="ref25933" refString="Curran, C. H. (1941 b) New American Syrphidae. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 78, 243 - 304." type="journal article">Curran (1941)</bibRefCitation>
described this species his 
<typeStatus id="1B7301F2E47AFF96FB62FD840813B104" box="[1274,1322,608,632]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">type</typeStatus>
specimen lacked its most distinctive attributes, i.e. the basoflagellomere and the apex of the abdomen, partly destroyed by pests.
</paragraph>
